## Step 3 — The main bumps (the core of it)

This is what actually matters. Merge each, **using a real merge commit** (no squash), and check both the version *and* that a bare tag was pushed.

| # | Merge to main | Last tag before | Expected VERSION | Expected tag created |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 11 | `release/minor-DM2026068056-EPAY-...` | `4.2.7` | `4.3.0` | `4.3.0` (bare, no `v`) |
| 12 | `release/major-DM2026070021-EPAY-...` | `4.3.0` | `5.0.0` | `5.0.0` |
| 13 | `hotfix/EPAY-6789-timeout-fix` | `5.0.0` | `5.0.1` | `5.0.1` |

For each, verify in the job log:
- `version` job prints `Semver: 4.2.7 → 4.3.0  (minor bump from release/minor-DM...)`
- `create-prod-tag` prints `✅ Production tag created: 4.3.0`
- Run `git tag -l` on the repo — confirm **bare** `4.3.0`, not `v4.3.0`
- `deploy-prod-dc`, `deploy-prod-dr`, `deploy-int` buttons appear

## Step 4 — Baseline test (fresh repo, no tags)

| # | Setup | Merge | Expected |
|---|---|---|---|
| 14 | Repo with **zero** semver tags | any `release/minor-...` → main | `1.0.0` exactly, tag `1.0.0` |

Delete your bootstrap tag temporarily, or use a second scratch repo.

## Step 5 — Failure gates (must fail — this is the point)

These prove the guards work. **All three must fail the pipeline.** If any of them *passes*, that's your bug.

| # | Test | How | Expected failure |
|---|---|---|---|
| 15 | **Gate 3 — squash** | Temporarily set main merge method to "Squash", merge a release, then set it back | version job fails: *"Squash or rebase merge was used"* |
| 16 | **Gate 2 — forbidden source** | Merge `feature/EPAY-1-x` directly to main | version job fails: *"Merge to main from unsupported source branch"* |
| 17 | **Invalid release type** | Try creating `release/patch-DM1-EPAY-x` | rejected by **push rule** (never reaches CI) |

Test 15 is the most important one you'll run. It confirms your load-bearing merge-method setting is actually guarded rather than silently producing wrong versions.

## Step 6 — Idempotency & concurrency

| # | Test | Expected |
|---|---|---|
| 18 | **Retry** a completed main pipeline | version job: *"Semver tag 4.3.0 already points at HEAD — reusing"*. `create-prod-tag`: *"idempotent skip"*. **No double-bump, no error.** |
| 19 | **Parallel merges** (if you can stage two release merges seconds apart) | One tags successfully. The other either serializes behind `prod-tag-lock` or fails with *"exists on a DIFFERENT commit — re-run"*. Re-running it computes from the new tag. |

Test 18 is easy and catches the nastiest class of bug (silent double-bump). Do it.

## Step 7 — Deployment (end to end)

Pick **one** service, then:

| # | Test | Verify |
|---|---|---|
| 20 | Click `deploy-sit` on a release push | Downstream deployment pipeline triggers, receives `VERSION=release-minor-dm...-<sha>` and `ENV=sit` |
| 21 | Click `deploy-preprod-dc` | receives `ENV=pre-prod-dc` |
| 22 | Click `deploy-preprod-dr` | receives `ENV=pre-prod` (the DR cluster — confirm it lands on the **DR** cluster, not DC) |
| 23 | Click `deploy-prod-dc` on a main pipeline | receives `ENV=prod-dc`, `VERSION=4.3.0` (bare semver) |
| 24 | Confirm image exists in JFrog | tag `4.3.0` for the prod build; `release-minor-dm...-<sha>` for the release build |

Test 22 specifically — since `pre-prod` and `pre-prod-dr` were a point of confusion, verify the DR deploy actually reaches the DR cluster and not preprod-DC.

